{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17517419","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17517419"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:53:03+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:53:03+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12798"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12798","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12798"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.69,0.16,0.01,0.14,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5239"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"46108"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5239","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5239"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12798"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"31031"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"12"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1165"},{"type":"tags","id":"2806"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"8911"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9248"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9749"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11628"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14973"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"46108","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/46108"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 25-year-old man presents to his General Practice clinic with a 12-month history of gradual onset low back pain. His pain is worse at night. He experiences morning stiffness, which does not improve with rest but he feels better after his swimming class. He has no other significant medical history and does not take any regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with a pulse rate of 87/min, blood pressure 125/90 mmHg, respiratory rate 22/min, and temperature 37.0\u00b0C. His chest expansion is normal. There is tenderness over his sacroiliac joints but otherwise no pain or restriction in spinal movement.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInvestigations reveal:\u003Cbr /\u003EESR 60 mm/hour (0-15)\u003Cbr /\u003ECRP 20 mg/L (0.3-10.0)\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate initial diagnostic investigation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["X-ray sacroiliac joints","CT lumbar spine and sacroiliac joints","DEXA scan","MRI sacroiliac joints","Bone scintigraphy"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe clinical scenario is consistent with axial spondyloarthritis, a chronic inflammatory disease of the axial spine that can manifest with various signs and symptoms. Chronic back pain and progressive spinal stiffness are the most common features. Involvement of the spine and sacroiliac (SI) joints, peripheral joints, digits, and entheses are characteristic. It is more common in men younger than 40 years and typically presents with back pain that is worse at night, associated with morning stiffness of more than 30 minutes. The pain can be aggravated by rest and relieved by exercise, especially swimming.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Eplain Xray of the SI joints\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate initial radiological test for diagnosing radiographic axial spondyloarthritis previously known as ankylosing spondylitis. It may show narrowing, sclerosis, erosions and ultimately ankylosis of the SI joints. The radiologist will Grade the SI joint changes. Changes may be slow to develop, but when present are diagnostic. Lumbar spine Xrays are often included and may show straightening of the spine and squaring of the vertebrae, but again these changes are not always visible in the early stages of the disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMRI of the SI joints\u003C/strong\u003E is used in the early diagnosis of sacroiliitis. It is the most accurate test for detecting bone marrow oedema and SI joint inflammation that occur early in the disease. However, MRI is a more specialised and expensive test that is not always readily available as an initial investigation in primary care.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECT of the lumbar spine and SI joints\u003C/strong\u003E is more specific than plain radiographs but less sensitive than MRI. It shows delineation of the SI joints and reveals more abnormalities and higher grades of sacroiliitis, but is most useful in patients with early disease of \u22643 years duration.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003EDEXA scan\u003C/strong\u003E is used to evaluate osteoporosis. \u003Cstrong\u003EBone scintigraphy\u003C/strong\u003E may be helpful in selected patients with normal or equivocal findings on SI joint radiographs. However, neither of these tests are indicated as an initial diagnostic investigation for suspected axial spondyloarthritis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Axial spondyloarthritis, a chronic, multisystem inflammatory disorder involving primarily the sacroiliac (SI) joints and the axial skeleton. X-ray of the SI joints is the most appropriate initial diagnostic investigation, although MRI is more accurate in early disease."],"references":["Wilfred C G  Peh, M.D. (2022) Ankylosing spondylitis imaging, Practice Essentials, Radiography, Computed Tomography. Medscape. Available at: https://emedicine.medscape.com/article/386639-overview (Accessed: May 6, 2023)."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"31031"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12798"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"31031","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/31031"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-05-28T20:18:09+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-09-03T17:59:32+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5239"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"46108"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"12","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/12"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc4b","name":"Rheumatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:47+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"30","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/30"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udff4\u200d\u2620\ufe0f","name":"Radiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-15T15:37:12+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitab